    sm_title: "Sources", sm_subtitle: "The probabilities weight 47.5% rankings, 47.5% bookmakers, 5% experts", sm_rank_h: "Team rankings (Elo)", sm_fifa_desc: "Team strength comes from an Elo rating computed over ~50,000 internationals. (The FIFA ranking was tested but added nothing beyond Elo, so it isn't used.)", sm_books: "Leading bookmakers", sm_books_desc: "Title odds collected late May 2026.", sm_experts_n: "Experts ({n})", sm_tips: "Picks as champion", sm_goal_h: "Goal model (draws)", sm_host_h: "Host advantage", ref_elo: "Rankings use the World Football Elo method (eloratings.net).", ref_books: "Market odds are among the most accurate outcome forecasts (Forrest, Goddard & Simmons, 2005).", ref_goal: "Scorelines use a Dixon–Coles goal model that corrects the low-score and draw bias (Dixon & Coles, 1997).", ref_host: "Host nations get a home edge — grounded in home-advantage research (Pollard, 1986); the size is calibrated on past World Cups.", sm_footer: "Data updated {date}. Probaball is not affiliated with or endorsed by FIFA.",
    hm_title: "How does Probaball work?", hm_subtitle: "The model behind the numbers, in brief", hm_h_idea: "The idea", hm_idea: "Nobody knows how the World Cup ends. So instead of guessing one winner, Probaball plays the whole tournament out over and over – thousands of times. Stronger teams win more often, and how often a team reaches a given round becomes its probability.", hm_h_strength: "How strong is a team?", hm_strength: "Each team's strength is a weighted blend (47.5% rankings, 47.5% bookmakers, 5% experts):", hm_li_fifa: "Rankings – an Elo rating from ~50,000 internationals (the FIFA ranking added nothing extra in tests).", hm_li_books: "Bookmakers – title odds from {books}, converted to probabilities.", hm_li_experts: "Experts – {n} well-known pundits and models (e.g. ESPN, Lineker, Opta).", hm_blend: "We combine the three into a single strength rating.", hm_h_match: "How is a match decided?", hm_match: "Goals are drawn at random (a Poisson model) where the stronger team is expected to score more. Host nations get a home edge in the group stage; knockout ties are settled on penalties.", hm_h_conviction: "Fixed matches", hm_conviction: "Convinced about a result? Add a fixed match – your team then wins every time those teams meet, and you see how the odds shift.", hm_h_note: "Good to know", hm_note: "This is a model, not a prophecy. Probaball is not affiliated with or endorsed by FIFA.",
    cc_eyebrow: "Your team", cc_stat: "{pct} to win the World Cup", cc_change: "Not my team — change", set_myteam: "Set as my team", is_myteam: "✓ Your team",
    how_link: "How does Probaball work?", code_link: "Open source", code_title: "Open source", code_subtitle: "The whole model and this site are open", code_lede: "A forecast is only as trustworthy as it is transparent. So the whole of Probaball — the data, the model, the simulation and this web app — is open source under the MIT license. Inspect it, question it, reuse it.", code_cta: "View the code on GitHub →", code_what_h: "What's in the repo", code_what_data: "Data ingestion — Elo from ~50,000 internationals, bookmaker title odds and expert picks, blended into each team's strength.", code_what_model: "The model — a Monte Carlo engine that plays the 48-team tournament out tens of thousands of times.", code_what_backtest: "Backtest & calibration — out-of-sample scoring (RPS) that referees every model change.", code_what_web: "The web app — this site (React + Vite), in six languages.", code_data_h: "Data & license", code_data: "Built on open and public sources. MIT-licensed. A statistical forecast, not a prediction — and not affiliated with or endorsed by FIFA.", theme_day: "☀️ Day", theme_night: "🌙 Night", lang_label: "Language",
    faq_q1: "How does Probaball work out who wins the 2026 World Cup?", faq_a1: "Probaball is a data-science simulation (Monte Carlo) that plays the entire 2026 World Cup out tens of thousands of times. Each team's strength is a weighted blend of three independent sources — team ratings (Elo, computed from ~50,000 internationals), bookmaker odds, and {n} experts' tips — and matches are decided by a Dixon-Coles goal model in the official knockout bracket. The share of simulations a team wins is its probability.",
    faq_q2: "Who are the favorites to win the 2026 World Cup?", faq_a2: "In Probaball's simulation {fav} is the favorite with {favPct}, followed by {second} and {third}. The order combines ranking, odds and expert tips.",
    faq_q3: "What are Probaball's odds based on?", faq_a3: "Three sources are weighted together (47.5% rankings, 47.5% bookmakers, 5% experts): team ratings led by Elo (the FIFA ranking turned out to add nothing extra in our tests), de-vigged title odds from {books}, and predictions from {n} experts and statistical models.",
    faq_q4: "Can I run my own simulation?", faq_a4: "Yes. You can adjust the parameters and force the outcome of individual matches, then re-run the data-science simulation to see how the probabilities change.",
    faq_q5: "Is Probaball affiliated with FIFA?", faq_a5: "No. Probaball is an independent data-science project and is not affiliated with or endorsed by FIFA.",
    faq_q6: 'How sophisticated is the model — and how accurate?', faq_a6: "Probaball blends many independent signals into one forecast — much like averaging many polls into a single estimate (a “poll of polls”). It draws on an Elo rating from ~50,000 internationals, market odds, expert models, a Dixon-Coles goal model and the official knockout bracket. Crucially, every improvement is tested against historical results (out-of-sample, via the Ranked Probability Score) and anything that doesn't actually predict better is dropped — the FIFA ranking and an attack/defence model both turned out to add nothing. But these are probabilities, not certainties: football is high-variance, and even a strong favorite usually sits below a 20% chance to win the whole thing.",
    tm_elo: 'Elo rating', gm_results: 'Likely outcomes', gm_matchday: 'Matchday {n}', gm_draw: 'Draw', gm_wins: '{team} win', gm_as_pred: 'as predicted', gm_upset: 'upset', gm_detail: 'detail', mm_score: 'Most likely score: {a}–{b}', mm_prematch: "Model's pre-match odds", gm_likely: 'likely {hg}–{ag}',
